{
  "id": "colinhacks_zod_5557",
  "repo_name": "colinhacks/zod",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/colinhacks/zod",
  "base_commit": "9712a6707f3d4584f222729965f3b78f076f0435",
  "pr_number": 5557,
  "issue_number": 5542,
  "issue_title": "z.iso.time with minute precision generates incompatible JSON Schema (format: \"time\")",
  "issue_body": "I don't know if this is intended behavior, but let's suppose that we have a zod schema that successfully validates a payload, should this payload also be successfully validated against the schema.toJsonSchema() representation?\n\nI ran into this issue while declaring a MCP tool using the **modelcontextprotocol/typescript-sdk** library, given the following example:\n\n```ts\n// Define a tool with structured output\nserver.registerTool(\n    'example_tool',\n    {\n        description: 'This is an example',\n        outputSchema: {\n            when: z.iso.time({ precision: -1 }),\n        }\n    },\n    async () => {\n        const untrustedPayload = { when: '14:31' };\n        const structuredContent = z.object({ when: z.iso.time({ precision: -1 }) }).parse(untrustedPayload);\n        return {\n            content: [\n                {\n                    type: 'text',\n                    text: JSON.stringify(structuredContent, null, 2)\n                }\n            ],\n            structuredContent\n        };\n    }\n    },\n);\n```\n\nSomehow, the debugging inspector provided by modelcontextprotocol was complaining about the response not being compliant with the tool output schema, even though it parsed properly, so after some investigation, I found why:\n\n```ts\nimport z from 'zod/v4';\nimport { Validator } from 'jsonschema';\n\nconst schema = z.object({\n  // Notice how we are setting precision: -1\n  when: z.iso.time({ precision: -1 }),\n});\n\nconst jsonSchema = schema.toJSONSchema();\n\nconst payload = {\n  when: '14:31',\n};\n\nschema.parse(payload);\nconsole.log('Payload was successfully validated!');\n\nconst validator = new Validator();\n\nconst { errors } = validator.validate(payload, jsonSchema);\nerrors.forEach((error) =>\n  console.log(`Error: ${error.property} ${error.message}`)\n);\n```\n\nOutput:\n```\nPayload was successfully validated!\nError: instance.when does not conform to the \"time\" format\n```\n\nIn this case, given that an hour without the amount of seconds does not comply with the json schema time definition, should the generated json schema definition use a regex pattern to validate the hour rather than the time format, when precision is different than zero?\n\nIt seems a bit misleading to me that the json schema does not successfully validate but the zod validation does, specially since the generated regex can be easily calculated given the precision, check this for reference:\n\n```ts\nz.iso.time({ precision: -1 }); // HH:MM (minute precision)\nz.iso.time({ precision: 0 });  // HH:MM:SS (second precision)\nz.iso.time({ precision: 1 });  // HH:MM:SS.s (decisecond precision)\nz.iso.time({ precision: 2 });  // HH:MM:SS.ss (centisecond precision)\nz.iso.time({ precision: 3 });  // HH:MM:SS.sss (millisecond precision)\n```",
  "merged_at": "2025-12-29T20:30:31Z",
